mpg01 = []
for i in Auto["mpg"]:
    if i > np.median(Auto["mpg"]):
        mpg01.append(1)
    if i < np.median(Auto["mpg"]):
        mpg01.append(0)

Auto["mpg01"]=mpg01

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

k_values = [1, 3, 5, 7, 9]
test_errors_knn = {}

for k in k_values:
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(X_train[["displacement","cylinders"]], y_train)
    y_knn_pred = knn.predict(X_test[["displacement","cylinders"]])
    test_accuracy_knn = accuracy_score(y_test, y_knn_pred)
    test_errors_knn[k] = 1 - test_accuracy_knn

print(test_errors_knn)

(c) Set a random seed, and then compute the LOOCV errors that result from ftting the following four models using least squares: i. Y = β0 + β1X + " ii. Y = β0 + β1X + β2X2 + " iii. Y = β0 + β1X + β2X2 + β3X3 + " iv. Y = β0 + β1X + β2X2 + β3X3 + β4X4 + ". Note you may fnd it helpful to use the data.frame() function to create a single data set containing both X and Y .

In [101]:
data = pd.DataFrame({'X': x, 'Y': y})
degrees = [1, 2, 3, 4]
loocv = LeaveOneOut()
loocv_errors = []

for i in degrees:
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(i)
    X_poly = poly.fit_transform(data[['X']])
    model = LinearRegression()
    
    squared_errors = []
    
    for train_index, test_index in loocv.split(X_poly):
        X_train, X_test = X_poly[train_index], X_poly[test_index]
        y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
        squared_errors.append((y_test - y_pred)**2)
    
    loocv_error = np.mean(squared_errors)
    loocv_errors.append(loocv_error)

loocv_df = pd.DataFrame({'Degree': degrees,'LOOCV Error': loocv_errors})
loocv_df

Chapter 6 Question 1¶

We perform best subset, forward stepwise, and backward stepwise selection on a single data set. For each approach, we obtain p + 1 models, containing 0, 1, 2,...,p predictors. Explain your answers:

(a) Which of the three models with k predictors has the smallest training RSS?

Best subset selection will produce the model has the smallest training RSS for any given k, because it examines all combinations of predictors.

(b) Which of the three models with k predictors has the smallest test RSS?

Backward stepwise selection might has the smallest test RSS, because the other two method has higher opportunity of over fitting.

(c) True or False:

i. The predictors in the k-variable model identifed by forward stepwise are a subset of the predictors in the (k+1)-variable model identifed by forward stepwise selection. TRUE

ii. The predictors in the k-variable model identifed by backward stepwise are a subset of the predictors in the (k + 1)- variable model identifed by backward stepwise selection. FALSE

iii. The predictors in the k-variable model identifed by backward stepwise are a subset of the predictors in the (k + 1)- variable model identifed by forward stepwise selection. FALSE

iv. The predictors in the k-variable model identifed by forward stepwise are a subset of the predictors in the (k+1)-variable model identifed by backward stepwise selection. FALSE

v. The predictors in the k-variable model identifed by best subset are a subset of the predictors in the (k + 1)-variable model identifed by best subset selection. FALSE

Chapter 6 Question 2¶

For parts (a) through (c), indicate which of i. through iv. is correct. Justify your answer.

(a) The lasso, relative to least squares, is:

iii is correct. Because lasso is used to select predictors it has more constrain, assigning the beta of some predictors to 0 can lead to the introduction of some bias.

(b) Repeat (a) for ridge regression relative to least squares

iii is correct. Because ridge regression introduces an L2 penalty on the regression coefficients, which shrinks them towards zero but does not force them to become exactly zero (it's more flexible than lasso but less than OLS). And if the reduction in variance is greater than the increase in bias, then the overall prediction accuracy will improve.

(c) Repeat (a) for non-linear methods relative to least squares.

i is correct. Because nonlinear models can capture more complex patterns in the data that linear models cannot, which reduces bias. When the complexity of the nonlinear model allows it to capture the true underlying patterns of the data without overfitting, the reduction in bias will outweigh the increase in variance, leading to better predictions.
